{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595959"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:08:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:08:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15385"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15385"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.05,0.14,0.14,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8076"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69319"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8076"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15385"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54772"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"6929"},{"type":"tags","id":"8509"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19607"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69319"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe enteric nervous system contains multiple types of neurons that regulate intestinal function. The submucosal plexus contains non-cholinergic secretomotor/vasodilatory neurons that control blood flow and secretion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the primary neurotransmitter in non-cholinergic secretomotor/vasodilatory neurons?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nitric oxide","Acetylcholine","Substance P","Vasoactive intestinal peptide","Serotonin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary neurotransmitter in non-cholinergic secretomotor/vasodilatory neurons is \u003Cstrong\u003Evasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP)\u003C/strong\u003E. VIP stimulates intestinal fluid and electrolyte secretion while simultaneously causing vasodilation of intestinal blood vessels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitric oxide\u003C/strong\u003E primarily functions as an inhibitory neurotransmitter causing smooth muscle relaxation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetylcholine\u003C/strong\u003E is the main neurotransmitter in cholinergic neurons controlling motility and secretion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubstance P\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in pain sensation and inflammatory responses\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerotonin\u003C/strong\u003E primarily initiates peristaltic and secretory reflexes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVIP-containing neurons form a distinct population that regulates intestinal blood flow and secretion independently of cholinergic pathways.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Vasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP) is the primary neurotransmitter in non-cholinergic secretomotor/vasodilatory submucosal neurons of the enteric nervous system.","VIP-containing neurons regulate intestinal blood flow and secretion independently of cholinergic pathways.","VIP stimulates fluid and electrolyte secretion while simultaneously causing vasodilation of intestinal blood vessels."],"references":["Chen BN, Humenick A, Yew WP, Peterson RA, Wiklendt L, Dinning PG, Spencer NJ, Wattchow DA, Costa M, Brookes SJH. Types of Neurons in the Human Colonic Myenteric Plexus Identified by Multilayer Immunohistochemical Coding. Cell Mol Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2023;16(4):573-605. doi: 10.1016/j.jcmgh.2023.06.010. Epub 2023 Jun 22. PMID: 37355216; PMCID: PMC10469081","Virtanen H, Garton DR, Andressoo JO. Myenteric Neurons Do Not Replicate in Small Intestine Under Normal Physiological Conditions in Adult Mouse. Cell Mol Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2022;14(1):27-34. doi: 10.1016/j.jcmgh.2022.04.001. Epub 2022 Apr 11. PMID: 35421596; PMCID: PMC9117811","Morarach K, Mikhailova A, Knoflach V, Memic F, Kumar R, Li W, Ernfors P, Marklund U. Diversification of molecularly defined myenteric neuron classes revealed by single-cell RNA sequencing. Nat Neurosci. 2021 Jan;24(1):34-46. doi: 10.1038/s41593-020-00736-x. Epub 2020 Dec 7. PMID: 33288908; PMCID: PMC7610403","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 SonsNightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54772"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15385"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54772"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T19:30:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T19:32:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8076"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69319"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},